WEBVTT

00:00.166 --> 00:03.735
[lively instrumental music]

00:03.738 --> 00:12.011
♪ ♪

00:37.203 --> 00:38.437
Good evening.

00:38.439 --> 00:40.105
I'm helen mirren,

00:40.107 --> 00:43.409
And you're watching
<i>documentary now!</i>

00:43.411 --> 00:45.077
For the past 50 years,

00:45.079 --> 00:47.479
<i>Documentary now!</i>
Has presented audiences

00:47.481 --> 00:50.816
With the world's
most thought-provoking cinema.

00:50.818 --> 00:54.186
This season, to celebrate
our golden anniversary,

00:54.188 --> 00:55.554
We take a look back at the films

00:55.556 --> 00:59.224
That helped shape, change,
and innovate

00:59.226 --> 01:01.193
The world of documentary.

01:01.195 --> 01:04.830
We begin with a story
of an inuit, a director,

01:04.831 --> 01:08.233
And how you can't always believe
what you see

01:08.235 --> 01:13.205
In the 1985 film
<i>kunuk uncovered.</i>

01:15.108 --> 01:18.110
[cheerful instrumental music]

01:18.112 --> 01:26.185
♪ ♪

01:30.557 --> 01:35.661
(male narrator)
in 1922, director
william h. Sebastian

01:35.663 --> 01:40.132
Introduced american audiences
to an eskimo named kunuk

01:40.134 --> 01:43.869
In the now-classic film
<i>kunuk the hunter.</i>

01:43.871 --> 01:45.604
♪ ♪

01:45.606 --> 01:49.875
It was groundbreaking cinema,
a box office success,

01:49.877 --> 01:53.345
And has been credited
with creating the genre

01:53.347 --> 01:56.849
That we now call documentary.

01:56.851 --> 02:01.286
But questions about kunuk
have always lingered.

02:01.288 --> 02:05.691
What was the relationship
between filmmaker and subject?

02:05.693 --> 02:09.527
Were the actions depicted
real or staged?

02:09.530 --> 02:13.632
Was the first documentary
a documentary at all?

02:13.634 --> 02:16.301
Or was it something else?

02:16.303 --> 02:21.173
Now, with new interviews
and recently recovered footage,

02:21.175 --> 02:23.775
We can finally know the answers.

02:23.777 --> 02:27.412
♪ ♪

02:32.185 --> 02:37.256
You have to understand
that in the early 1920s,

02:37.258 --> 02:40.592
Everyone had eskimo fever.

02:40.594 --> 02:42.194
[laughs]

02:42.196 --> 02:44.530
If you were hosting
an exposition

02:44.532 --> 02:48.400
And your exposition had
an eskimo in it,

02:48.402 --> 02:51.336
People would line up
around the block

02:51.338 --> 02:53.405
For a chance to see it.

02:53.407 --> 02:56.475
I remember my william saying

02:56.477 --> 03:00.679
That seeing an eskimo
in london or new york

03:00.681 --> 03:03.215
Would never be as exciting

03:03.217 --> 03:06.818
As seeing them
in their natural settings.

03:06.820 --> 03:10.689
If he could find a way
to do that, he said,

03:10.691 --> 03:13.559
He could make a fortune.

03:13.561 --> 03:17.496
[harp and flute music]

03:17.498 --> 03:20.365
At the time, I had just finished
shooting a film

03:20.367 --> 03:22.734
Called <i> passing train.</i>

03:22.736 --> 03:24.770
It was playing to much fanfare
in europe.

03:24.772 --> 03:26.672
[train horn blows]

03:26.674 --> 03:29.942
And sebastian saw the film,
and he contacted me.

03:29.944 --> 03:31.476
No one had ever shot a film

03:31.478 --> 03:33.645
In the conditions
he was proposing,

03:33.647 --> 03:36.248
But I could tell
he had a vision.

03:36.250 --> 03:39.952
He would use words like
"realism" and "truth,"

03:39.954 --> 03:43.355
And at that time, those words
meant a great deal to me.

03:43.357 --> 03:46.658
And, uh, two weeks later,
we arrived in canada.

03:46.660 --> 03:48.293
I just took the job.

03:48.295 --> 03:51.563
♪ ♪

03:51.565 --> 03:55.467
(man)
"dearest meredith,
tomorrow we reach st. George.

03:55.469 --> 03:57.302
"I am trembling with excitement.

03:57.304 --> 03:58.737
"the very idea of committing

03:58.739 --> 04:00.639
"these funny little monsters
to film

04:00.641 --> 04:04.810
Brings a smile to my face
even as my heart aches for you."

04:04.812 --> 04:07.012
(scott)
when we finally arrived
at the trading post,

04:07.014 --> 04:09.281
He told me to set up my camera

04:09.283 --> 04:11.683
And rounded up
some local hunters.

04:11.685 --> 04:14.620
Now, sebastian thought
a good scene for his film

04:14.622 --> 04:16.688
Would be eskimos being puzzled

04:16.690 --> 04:19.391
By where the sound came
from a gramophone.

04:19.392 --> 04:20.625
This really delighted him.

04:20.628 --> 04:22.494
He thought that was
a funny idea.

04:22.496 --> 04:24.429
They all thought
he was some sort of clown.

04:24.431 --> 04:26.932
I mean, these eskimos
were--were laughing,

04:26.934 --> 04:28.700
And he didn't care
for their laughter.

04:28.702 --> 04:31.903
See, sebastian is so--
a dude of his size advantage,

04:31.905 --> 04:35.374
He could impose his will
physically on the eskimo.

04:35.376 --> 04:37.542
But they were a wiry lot,
I tell ya.

04:37.544 --> 04:38.810
They just kicked the crap
out of him.

04:38.812 --> 04:40.746
They shoved snow in his mouth.

04:40.748 --> 04:41.947
They'd shove it in his butt.

04:41.949 --> 04:43.548
They cold-cocked him,

04:43.550 --> 04:45.751
Where they put his member
in a block of ice

04:45.753 --> 04:47.386
And then stomped on it.

04:47.388 --> 04:50.555
The letters from sebastian
at this time

04:50.557 --> 04:52.658
Were very dire.

04:52.660 --> 04:54.960
He was intent on coming home

04:54.962 --> 04:58.430
With nothing to show
for his travels.

04:58.432 --> 05:00.065
(scott)
he told me he wanted a drink,

05:00.067 --> 05:03.335
And I was against it,
but I'll admit I gave it to him,

05:03.337 --> 05:04.870
'cause that's the kind of guy
I was.

05:04.872 --> 05:06.338
I was a big enabler,

05:06.340 --> 05:08.807
And if you were trying
to kick a habit,

05:08.809 --> 05:10.642
I gave you the thing you wanted.

05:10.644 --> 05:12.978
Anyways, then we noticed
the men in the village

05:12.980 --> 05:14.880
Leaving en masse,

05:14.882 --> 05:17.316
And we were told
that they were departing

05:17.318 --> 05:19.351
For a months-long hunt.

05:19.353 --> 05:22.587
And it was at that moment I saw,
amongst the womenfolk,

05:22.589 --> 05:25.090
A solitary man waving.

05:25.092 --> 05:27.559
♪ ♪

05:27.561 --> 05:31.663
And that was pipilok,
and he saved our film, yeah.

05:31.665 --> 05:32.931
(man)
"my dearest meredith,

05:32.933 --> 05:34.966
"fortune has smiled upon us.

05:34.968 --> 05:37.402
"I have discovered
the star of our film.

05:37.404 --> 05:40.939
"he is slow of mind, but this
makes him a malleable subject

05:40.941 --> 05:42.808
That I can make do what I wish."

05:42.810 --> 05:44.976
(scott)
there was an eskimo girl
who spoke a little english,

05:44.978 --> 05:47.612
And we hired her
to be our translator.

05:47.614 --> 05:52.617
I agreed to translate,
but I told them it was a mistake

05:52.619 --> 05:54.486
To work with pipilok.

05:54.488 --> 05:57.522
The gods had cursed him
in the head.

05:57.524 --> 06:00.692
♪ ♪

06:00.694 --> 06:03.595
(scott)
pipilok was everything
sebastian wanted and more.

06:03.597 --> 06:05.797
If you handed him a prop
of any kind,

06:05.799 --> 06:09.000
He would take it and use it
as something else.

06:09.002 --> 06:12.003
[cheerful string trio music]

06:12.005 --> 06:16.541
♪ ♪

06:16.543 --> 06:18.377
Sebastian always insisted

06:18.379 --> 06:20.712
He wanted the film
to have comic moments.

06:20.714 --> 06:23.515
That was a phrase he used,
"comic moments."

06:23.517 --> 06:26.651
Pipilok, he was perfect
at those.

06:26.653 --> 06:28.453
♪ ♪

06:28.455 --> 06:31.390
But if you needed eskimos
doing eskimo things,

06:31.392 --> 06:33.024
He was not your guy.

06:33.026 --> 06:36.461
I mean, there was a reason
pipilok wasn't on the hunt

06:36.463 --> 06:38.430
With the rest of the men
in the village.

06:40.900 --> 06:42.968
He wasn't just bad
at being an eskimo;

06:42.970 --> 06:44.736
I mean, there was something
fundamentally wrong

06:44.738 --> 06:46.438
With this guy.

06:46.440 --> 06:54.513
♪ ♪

07:13.199 --> 07:15.834
I figured,
"well, the game is up."

07:15.836 --> 07:18.870
We tried, but this wasn't
an eskimo to make a movie about.

07:18.872 --> 07:21.173
But sebastian, he--
he didn't agree.

07:21.175 --> 07:24.709
He tied pipilok's wrists
to the handles,

07:24.711 --> 07:26.912
And he nailed the soles
of his boots

07:26.914 --> 07:28.814
To the bottom of the sled.

07:28.816 --> 07:31.817
Yeah, I saw this.

07:31.819 --> 07:34.920
[dramatic music]

07:34.922 --> 07:37.022
It's one of
the most famous shots

07:37.024 --> 07:39.758
In one of the most famous films
ever made,

07:39.760 --> 07:41.993
And all I ever remember
are the sounds of his screams.

07:41.995 --> 07:45.764
Boy, he was howling
across the tundra and back,

07:45.766 --> 07:47.132
Screaming.

07:47.134 --> 07:50.502
"aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaah."

07:54.707 --> 07:57.642
[light classical music]

07:57.644 --> 08:03.014
♪ ♪

08:03.016 --> 08:05.617
(qamaniq)
sebastian would brag
to the women

08:05.619 --> 08:09.921
That he was making a real film
with real people,

08:09.923 --> 08:12.858
But everything they did
was fake.

08:12.860 --> 08:14.993
(scott)
for the famous
spear-hunting scene,

08:14.995 --> 08:17.496
Sebastian would have
several eskimo women

08:17.498 --> 08:18.997
Submerged underwater.

08:18.999 --> 08:21.066
When pipilok put his spear in,

08:21.068 --> 08:23.702
They had to stick a fish
on the end of it.

08:23.704 --> 08:26.905
I was a little anxious
and, uh, distressed

08:26.907 --> 08:29.107
By the direction
I thought the film was going,

08:29.109 --> 08:31.109
And I tried to speak
to sebastian,

08:31.111 --> 08:33.979
But at this point, he--you know,
he was drinking even more,

08:33.981 --> 08:35.280
And he started taking up

08:35.282 --> 08:37.215
With many of the local
village women.

08:37.217 --> 08:39.818
He always talked about
how fat they were

08:39.820 --> 08:42.020
And how they looked like guys.

08:42.022 --> 08:45.857
Ugly women, the eskimo.

08:45.859 --> 08:48.760
My god, they were ugly.

08:48.762 --> 08:50.862
I [bleep] about three of 'em.

08:50.864 --> 08:52.797
(man)
"my dearest meredith,

08:52.799 --> 08:55.066
"we are capturing
the true eskimo tradition

08:55.068 --> 08:57.669
Like no one ever before."

08:57.671 --> 09:01.273
(meredith)
he was very pleased
with how it was going,

09:01.275 --> 09:03.108
But he wanted to make certain

09:03.110 --> 09:06.745
That it looked
as good as he hoped.

09:06.747 --> 09:08.647
Sebastian had sent the film
to be developed,

09:08.649 --> 09:11.550
And the first few reels
made their way back to us.

09:11.552 --> 09:15.020
[flute music]

09:15.022 --> 09:17.923
(qamaniq)
when sebastian showed us
the film,

09:17.925 --> 09:19.824
We all laughed.

09:19.826 --> 09:24.963
How silly it was that pipilok
looked like a hunter.

09:24.965 --> 09:28.066
But pipilok was not laughing.

09:28.068 --> 09:29.634
(scott)
after we watched the footage,

09:29.636 --> 09:30.835
I asked pipilok what he thought.

09:30.837 --> 09:33.605
He told me there was no pipilok.

09:33.607 --> 09:35.874
There was only kunuk.

09:35.876 --> 09:37.709
Whoa.

09:37.711 --> 09:39.010
(man)
"dearest meredith,

09:39.012 --> 09:40.679
"the most adorable thing
happened

09:40.681 --> 09:42.247
"at the screening last night.

09:42.249 --> 09:44.049
"pipilok now believes

09:44.051 --> 09:46.751
"he is the hunter
we have made him out to be.

09:46.753 --> 09:49.788
"he has started referring
to himself as kunuk

09:49.790 --> 09:51.690
And insists we do the same."

09:51.692 --> 09:53.625
(scott)
we all thought it was funny
that night,

09:53.627 --> 09:55.994
But the next morning,
as we were setting up

09:55.996 --> 09:58.296
For a shot of pipilok emerging
from his igloo,

09:58.298 --> 10:00.332
He wouldn't come out.

10:00.334 --> 10:02.934
(qamaniq)
pipilok explained that he
thought he looked too old

10:02.936 --> 10:06.605
In the footage he had seen
the night before.

10:06.607 --> 10:10.609
There was a prostitute in town
who painted her face.

10:10.611 --> 10:16.348
He suggested sebastian hire her
to make his face look younger.

10:16.350 --> 10:18.650
(scott)
took me upwards of an hour
to explain

10:18.652 --> 10:21.119
That we wanted to pay her
for something that wasn't sex.

10:21.121 --> 10:24.956
Kunuk was such a sweet man.

10:24.958 --> 10:29.861
Simple, fragile, but sweet.

10:29.863 --> 10:34.199
[lilting string music]

10:34.201 --> 10:37.636
(scott)
the shots we did get that day
were completely unusable

10:37.638 --> 10:39.170
For obvious reasons.

10:39.172 --> 10:41.306
♪ ♪

10:41.308 --> 10:43.975
And that was just the beginning
of things going south,

10:43.977 --> 10:45.243
I tell you.

10:45.245 --> 10:47.112
(man)
"the whore has convinced pipilok

10:47.114 --> 10:50.015
"that we shouldn't have to wait
until the end of the day to eat.

10:50.017 --> 10:51.950
"now he insists
that we have a table

10:51.952 --> 10:54.352
"with coffee
and other craft services

10:54.354 --> 10:57.122
To enjoy in the downtime
between shooting."

10:57.124 --> 10:58.990
(qamaniq)
you could sense

10:58.992 --> 11:02.894
That sebastian felt he was
losing control over his film.

11:02.896 --> 11:05.063
But he was stronger
than pipilok,

11:05.065 --> 11:08.233
So he used that
to his advantage.

11:08.235 --> 11:13.071
(claudette)
sebastian was, if nothing else,
a bully.

11:13.073 --> 11:15.206
For the next hour,
things went smoothly

11:15.208 --> 11:17.042
Until marie's pimp showed up.

11:17.044 --> 11:18.443
Oh, boy, now, this guy.

11:18.445 --> 11:20.345
[dramatic music]

11:20.347 --> 11:22.280
He called himself chacal,

11:22.282 --> 11:24.015
Which is french for "jackal."

11:24.017 --> 11:26.418
It turns out
after sebastian hit pipilok,

11:26.420 --> 11:28.920
Marie went straight into town
to get him.

11:28.922 --> 11:34.059
(meredith)
he felt outraged that the eskimo
wasn't being compensated.

11:34.061 --> 11:37.162
Sebastian said,
"that's not how it works."

11:37.164 --> 11:40.899
And the man struck him
across the face.

11:40.901 --> 11:47.972
♪ ♪

11:50.376 --> 11:51.476
(scott)
from that day on,

11:51.478 --> 11:53.812
Chacal became pipilok's manager.

11:53.814 --> 11:56.081
Making matters worse,
chacal decided

11:56.083 --> 11:58.083
That marie needed to be
in the film.

11:58.085 --> 12:02.854
(qamaniq)
I remember overhearing
sebastian say to chacal,

12:02.856 --> 12:05.423
"what would she play, anyway?"

12:05.425 --> 12:10.428
Chacal said, "she can play
the [bleep] queen of the eskimos

12:10.430 --> 12:12.297
"for all I care,

12:12.299 --> 12:15.100
But she's going to be
in the picture."

12:15.102 --> 12:18.103
[soft classical music]

12:18.105 --> 12:22.307
♪ ♪

12:22.309 --> 12:24.809
(scott)
at that point, it was getting
very difficult to shoot.

12:24.811 --> 12:27.479
Pipilok would only work
four hours a day.

12:27.481 --> 12:30.749
I mean, I was about to tell
sebastian, "hey, I'm leaving."

12:30.751 --> 12:32.517
And then the men came back
from the hunt.

12:32.519 --> 12:34.119
Remember them?

12:34.121 --> 12:36.421
[dramatic bassoon music]

12:36.423 --> 12:39.190
Now, sebastian had left pieces
of his clothing

12:39.192 --> 12:42.060
In pretty much every igloo
in the village,

12:42.062 --> 12:44.395
And I figured he was a dead man.

12:44.397 --> 12:48.266
Sebastian had to leave
in the dark of the night.

12:48.268 --> 12:52.337
The women gave him some blankets
and some food

12:52.339 --> 12:55.874
But assumed he would just die
in the woods.

12:55.876 --> 12:58.309
That was okay.

12:58.311 --> 13:00.812
At first, it was fun for them

13:00.814 --> 13:03.548
To be sleeping
with a fancy white man,

13:03.550 --> 13:09.888
But they told me he needed a lot
of positive feedback sexually.

13:09.890 --> 13:12.123
That got tiresome.

13:12.125 --> 13:14.459
(scott)
when I realized
sebastian had gone,

13:14.461 --> 13:17.829
I once again thought,
"well, hey, that's it.

13:17.831 --> 13:19.898
End of that.
I'm going home."

13:19.900 --> 13:23.468
But then chacal approaches me,
and he says, uh--he says, uh,

13:23.470 --> 13:26.137
"I want to speak to you
about my client."

13:26.139 --> 13:28.072
I say, "go ahead."

13:28.074 --> 13:32.210
And he tells me that pipilok
would like to direct.

13:32.212 --> 13:34.345
I just laughed in his face.

13:34.347 --> 13:37.816
But I tell you, what I saw next
completely changed my mind.

13:37.818 --> 13:40.518
Pipilok had put the camera
on a sled.

13:40.520 --> 13:43.154
I asked him what he was doing,
and he explained

13:43.156 --> 13:46.524
That if that sled ran
alongside the sled he was on,

13:46.526 --> 13:49.160
It would make for
a more interesting shot.

13:49.162 --> 13:50.929
And he was right, of course.

13:50.931 --> 13:55.300
[harp flourish]

13:55.302 --> 13:57.969
After we finished shooting,
I slapped him on the back,

13:57.971 --> 13:59.537
And I told him

13:59.539 --> 14:01.873
He had just changed the way
films were gonna be made.

14:01.875 --> 14:04.275
And the next thing he said to me
was so jarring,

14:04.277 --> 14:07.145
I had to have aglatki
translate it twice.

14:07.147 --> 14:10.381
"we can grab each other's asses
later.

14:10.383 --> 14:12.217
Let's make a film."

14:12.219 --> 14:14.919
(scott)
there were more filmmaking
innovations made

14:14.921 --> 14:16.387
In the next three days

14:16.389 --> 14:18.923
Than there were in the previous
three years, I tell you.

14:18.925 --> 14:20.625
(qamaniq)
pipilok felt strongly

14:20.627 --> 14:23.361
That the camera should see
what he was seeing.

14:23.363 --> 14:27.031
He kept calling it
his point of view.

14:27.033 --> 14:28.499
(scott)
he strapped the camera

14:28.501 --> 14:30.501
To the front of the sled,
facing out.

14:30.503 --> 14:33.304
We flipped it around
so it was facing pipilok.

14:33.306 --> 14:35.607
For the seal-hunting scene,

14:35.609 --> 14:38.610
He wanted the camera having
the point of view of the seal.

14:38.612 --> 14:40.144
I told him there was no way

14:40.146 --> 14:42.213
I was getting in the water
with my camera.

14:42.215 --> 14:45.016
He laughed at me, and he said,
"we'll build a set."

14:45.018 --> 14:48.453
And we did, and it was amazing,
of course.

14:48.455 --> 14:51.890
But no one knew that
more than he did, I tell you.

14:59.068 --> 15:00.935
I was on assignment

15:00.937 --> 15:02.370
With the bureau
of american ethnography.

15:02.372 --> 15:03.738
We were traveling
across country,

15:03.740 --> 15:06.608
Interviewing indigenous people
at the time.

15:06.610 --> 15:08.410
I had just arrived at st. George

15:08.412 --> 15:10.645
When I heard
a film was being shot.

15:10.647 --> 15:14.416
I was intrigued, of course,
and found my way to their set.

15:14.418 --> 15:16.718
Pipilok wanted to record sound
for the film,

15:16.720 --> 15:19.087
Not music but actual dialog.

15:19.089 --> 15:22.023
I said, "pipilok,
that's not how it works."

15:22.025 --> 15:25.593
I explained who I was,
and his eyes went wide.

15:25.595 --> 15:29.597
I started immediately.

15:29.599 --> 15:31.800
When pipilok fired marie,

15:31.802 --> 15:33.868
She was very surprised.

15:33.870 --> 15:37.672
He told me he was making a film
with realism and truth

15:37.674 --> 15:40.909
And that a white woman had
no place in it.

15:40.911 --> 15:43.011
(qamaniq)
marie had told chacal

15:43.013 --> 15:45.647
She had been fired
from the film.

15:45.649 --> 15:49.951
He came to the set
to put pipilok straight.

15:49.953 --> 15:52.954
[suspenseful music]

15:52.956 --> 16:01.029
♪ ♪

16:05.000 --> 16:07.669
Being a director
turned him into a tyrant.

16:07.671 --> 16:12.107
(qamaniq)
pipilok hired nuka
to be his leading actress.

16:12.109 --> 16:15.410
He wanted a shot of her
holding a baby

16:15.412 --> 16:19.814
In such a way that the sun would
hit her just right.

16:19.816 --> 16:22.150
(scott)
pipilok didn't like the way
nuka was doing it.

16:22.152 --> 16:24.486
He kept telling her
that it was artless.

16:58.821 --> 17:01.089
He was very angry.

17:04.026 --> 17:05.693
(scott)
he was becoming
completely unglued.

17:05.694 --> 17:07.494
He started working
with his shirt off

17:07.497 --> 17:08.963
Despite the bitter cold,

17:08.964 --> 17:10.531
And when we asked him about it,

17:10.534 --> 17:13.968
He would say things like,
"I am the cold.

17:13.970 --> 17:15.703
"I am the northern wind.

17:15.704 --> 17:17.539
I am kunuk."

17:17.540 --> 17:19.874
And you have to remember
his name wasn't kunuk.

17:19.876 --> 17:21.142
It was pipilok.

17:21.144 --> 17:24.112
[dramatic percussive music]

17:24.114 --> 17:26.448
The day of the blizzard, I said,
"well, he's not gonna shoot."

17:26.450 --> 17:27.882
And he did.

17:27.884 --> 17:30.151
He kept yelling at us
that we were cowards.

17:30.153 --> 17:32.654
He was going out there
with or without us.

17:32.656 --> 17:36.057
He kept saying the blizzard
would fix all of the--

17:36.059 --> 17:37.459
What was the term?

17:37.461 --> 17:39.861
The third-act problems.

17:39.863 --> 17:42.063
Alexander said,
"well, he's an eskimo.

17:42.065 --> 17:43.765
At least he knows
what he's doing."

17:43.767 --> 17:46.134
And I remember thinking,
"he's not an eskimo.

17:46.136 --> 17:47.202
"he's an idiot.

17:47.204 --> 17:48.636
He's gonna die."

17:48.638 --> 17:51.639
[dramatic music]

17:51.641 --> 17:57.212
♪ ♪

17:57.214 --> 18:00.849
(krauss)
it was the worst storm
in half a century.

18:00.851 --> 18:03.218
Ships in the dock
had been unmoored

18:03.220 --> 18:05.520
And lost to the sea.

18:05.522 --> 18:07.589
He never stood a chance.

18:07.591 --> 18:10.191
(scott)
we never found him
or the camera, no.

18:10.193 --> 18:12.727
But we had the film.

18:12.729 --> 18:14.262
Thank god I had that film.

18:14.264 --> 18:15.997
I kept the film.

18:15.999 --> 18:17.699
How about that?

18:21.770 --> 18:23.938
When barnabas left, he asked

18:23.940 --> 18:25.874
If there was anything
he could do for me.

18:25.876 --> 18:29.077
(scott)
what she wanted was
an associate producer's credit.

18:29.079 --> 18:31.779
I didn't know what that was,
so I said yes.

18:31.781 --> 18:35.083
I walked barnabas to the docks
to wish him good-bye.

18:35.085 --> 18:37.185
And while we were waiting
for his ship,

18:37.187 --> 18:39.954
We were approached
by the most filthy beggar.

18:39.956 --> 18:41.689
(scott)
despite the beard and the hair,

18:41.691 --> 18:43.691
I knew it was sebastian
immediately.

18:43.693 --> 18:46.661
I mean, he was covered in feces,
his own.

18:46.663 --> 18:49.964
When I asked him why, he said,
"to keep the wolves away."

18:49.966 --> 18:52.066
I mean, he had really gone nuts.

18:52.068 --> 18:53.835
(krauss)
barnabas cleaned him up

18:53.837 --> 18:56.604
And bought him a ticket home.

18:56.606 --> 18:58.306
It's more
than I would have done;

18:58.308 --> 18:59.807
I'll tell you that much.

18:59.809 --> 19:01.209
(scott)
we returned home,

19:01.211 --> 19:02.877
And I tell you I was so excited

19:02.879 --> 19:05.847
For sebastian to see
what pipilok had shot.

19:05.849 --> 19:08.850
[sweeping music]

19:08.852 --> 19:16.925
♪ ♪

19:44.887 --> 19:46.654
And he hated it,

19:46.656 --> 19:48.189
Said it was too unsettling,

19:48.191 --> 19:50.858
Told me to burn it all,
to burn it!

19:50.860 --> 19:54.362
The only thing sebastian kept,
of everything pipilok did,

19:54.364 --> 19:55.763
Was the name kunuk.

19:55.765 --> 19:57.198
He liked the name kunuk.

19:57.200 --> 20:00.168
[musical fanfare]

20:00.170 --> 20:02.103
(meredith)
it was a hit.

20:02.105 --> 20:05.039
When the film ended
the opening night,

20:05.041 --> 20:07.208
People leapt to their feet

20:07.210 --> 20:12.046
And demanded they start it again
from the beginning.

20:12.048 --> 20:14.916
(scott)
there's no accounting for taste,
is there?

20:14.918 --> 20:17.318
Here was a film
not a tenth as good

20:17.320 --> 20:19.621
As the one
we could have showed them,

20:19.623 --> 20:20.989
And they ate it up.

20:20.991 --> 20:24.058
Audiences--
they're [bleep] useless.

20:24.060 --> 20:28.363
(meredith)
he didn't live long enough
to enjoy his success.

20:28.365 --> 20:31.733
He died two weeks
after the premiere

20:31.735 --> 20:35.236
With what the physician said
was...

20:35.238 --> 20:36.337
[sighs]

20:36.339 --> 20:39.240
"all the gonorrhea."

20:39.242 --> 20:41.943
He was a silly man.

20:45.214 --> 20:48.282
Made a great film, though.

20:50.986 --> 20:53.988
[gentle music]

20:53.990 --> 21:02.063
♪ ♪
